burlap.oomdp.stochasticgames.agentactions

Class GroundedSGAgentAction

  • java.lang.Object
    • burlap.oomdp.stochasticgames.agentactions.GroundedSGAgentAction
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AbstractGroundedAction
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ObParamSGAgentAction.GroundedObParamSGAgentAction

    public class GroundedSGAgentAction
extends java.lang.Object
implements AbstractGroundedAction
    A GroundedSGAgentAction is a high-level implementation of the AbstractGroundedAction that is closely associated with the SGAgentAction definition of actions that can be taken by agents in a multi-agent stochastic game. The role of a GroundedSGAgentAction is to provide a reference to a corresponding SGAgentAction, a reference to the name of the agent who is taking the action, and any other parameter assignment information that is necessary for the agent to apply the action. The set of possible GroundedSGAgentAction instances specifying the set of possible parameter assignments an acting action can apply will be generated by the associated SGAgentAction method SGAgentAction.getAllApplicableGroundedActions(burlap.oomdp.core.states.State, String). See the SGAgentAction class documentation for more information on defining parameterized SGAgentActions.

    This high-level class can be used directly, without subclassing, for any parameter-less SGAgentAction definitions and should be subclassed for any parameterized SGAgentAction definitions (with the subclass instances returned by the associated SGAgentAction.getAllApplicableGroundedActions(burlap.oomdp.core.states.State, String) and SGAgentAction.getAssociatedGroundedAction(String) method). The GroundedSGAgentAction subclass can store the parameter assignment data any way you like.

    If you plan on making an SGAgentAction definition with OO-MDP object parameters, you can use the existing ObParamSGAgentAction, which is associated with the GroundedAction subclass ObParamSGAgentAction.GroundedObParamSGAgentAction.

    When you subclass a GroundedSGAgentAction to provide parameter information you should override the following methods.
    isParameterized()
    copy()
    initParamsWithStringRep(String[])
    getParametersAsString()
    The isParameterized() method should be overridden to return true if your subclass is parameterized. The copy() method should be override to return a new instance of your subclass with all parameter assignment information copied over. The initParamsWithStringRep(String[]) should be overridden to allow a String array specification of parameters to be provided to initialize them. Overriding this method is not critical, but is useful for serialization purposes. The getParametersAsString() similarly should returns a String array representing the String value of each parameter. As with the initParamsWithStringRep(String[]) method, overriding getParametersAsString() is not critical, but is useful for serialization and similar processes.

    James MacGlashan
